	<article>
	<title> Blam! Blam! </title>
	<text>
		<para>
			Mikael Hallendal has been furiously hacking on his new project called
			"Blam!", a RSS Aggregator for MATE. He has already made two releases,
			and he claims "Yeah I know, BLAM! is no longer just an Application, it's 				becoming a Life Style!". Blam requires Mono and GTK# to be installed
			in your machine.
		</para>
		<para>
			Great work by Mikael - and maybe now everyone can watch what the MATE
			hackers are doing by having their blogs right on their desktops, in
			a neatly organised manner. A satisfied Blam! user comments - "Before
			BLAM!, I was like a lost sheep in the MATE world. But after
			installing BLAM!, I know what everyone is doing, including the
			super-famous Robert Love!" ;-)
		</para>
		<link>http://micke.hallendal.net/archives/000104.html</link>
		<link>http://micke.hallendal.net/archives/blam-0.1-1.html</link>
	</text>
	</article>

	<article>
	<title> Get acquainted with Gstreamer </title>
	<text>
		<para>
			Get familiarised with one of the most cool components of the MATE
			Desktop. Christian Schaller has written a very nice introductory article
			on Gstreamer, explaining what it is, and what it is supposed to do.
			(I hear that even the KDE hackers are thinking about gstreamer - good for
			them). :-)
		</para>
		<link>http://www.osnews.com/story.php?news_id=5648</link>
	</text>
	</article>

	<article>
	<title> MATE-Network developers think about a code reorganisation</title>
	<text>
		<para>
			The MATE Network hackers are thinking about the separation of the
			various tools in their own CVS modules, with their own releases and
			maintainers. This will avoid having MATE Network being a giant,
			unmaintainable module. They are also considering merging  the remote
			shell client with MATE terminal, making the remote desktop client
			better integrated into the desktop and making the Personal Web Server
			an extension to Caja, so a 'Share' menu item shows up in the
			Caja context menu for folders.
		</para>
		<link>http://rodrigo.mate-db.org/news.php?14/January/2004</link>
	</text>
	</article>

	<article>
	<title> MATE Volume Manager lands in CVS </title>
	<text>
		<para>
			Robert Love has transferred the code for MATE Volume Manager into the
			MATE CVS. The MATE Volume Manager is a simple MATE daemon that acts
			as a policy agent on top of the Project Utopia stack, which includes the
			kernel, hotplug, udev, and HAL. MATE Volume Manager listens for HAL
			events and responds with user-configurable reactions.
		</para>
		<para>
			RML has also created a few RPMs for Fedora Core, and you can give it a
			spin, keeping in mind that these are really bleeding edge, there will
			be bugs.
		</para>
		<link>http://primates.ximian.com/~rml/blog/archives/000315.html</link>
		<link>http://primates.ximian.com/~rml/project_utopia/fedora/</link>
	</text>
	</article>

	<article>
	  <title> Planner gets support libgda </title>
	<text>
		<para>
			Alvaro del Castillo has committed his work in replacing the code that accesses postgres
			directly with libgda allowing Planner (formerly known as Mr. Project) to use any kind of
			database that libgda supports.
		</para>
		<para>
			 Planner is a tool for planning, scheduling and tracking projects. Planner is an open source project targetting the MATE Desktop.
		</para>
		<link>http://planner.imendio.org</link>
	</text>
	</article>

